Once server is up we see that data such as version information are not accurate in zaproxy. We can cross-source with wappalyzer that is much more accurate
Once we created a new context for our webpage and performed a spider attack we notice that the spider found the login page (wp-login.php). It also tried a POST request to connect using ZAP credentials as username and password.
On the login page we notice that the error message is not the same wether it is a valid username or not, meaning we get to know what usernames do exist.
We decide to fuzz the login page with different common usernames
To do so we click on the POST request, highlight the username ZAP > right click > fuzz and we add a few strings manually such as user,wordpress,admin

In the fuzzet menu we also go to the section message processor and add a tag creator "not registered" in the two fields."not registered" is part of the logging error we get when the username is not registered
We get that admin i registered from the fuzzing attack. We click on it and go to password section to perform a new fuzzing attack on it
